us formation; however, rigid fixation that suppresses interfragmentary movement (IFM) can limit callus formation, thereby impairing the healing process.","target":"Long bone fractures, such as those of the femur, heal through external callus formation; however, rigid fixation that suppresses interfragmentary movement (IFM) can limit callus formation, thereby impairing the healing process.","line":12},{"title":"Mechanotransduction involves cells within the fracture callus detecting mechanical signals in their environment and triggering biological responses such as cell proliferation, differentiation, and matrix synthesis.","target":"Mechanotransduction involves cells within the fracture callus detecting mechanical signals in their environment and triggering biological responses such as cell proliferation, differentiation, and matrix synthesis.","line":12},{"title":"Tissue development in the fracture callus depends on its tolerance to local strain (which is uneven and changes during healing), with new tissues stiffening the fracture, reducing strain, and promoting bone formation.","target":"Tissue development in the fracture callus depends on its tolerance to local strain (which is uneven and changes during healing), with new tissues stiffening the fracture, reducing strain, and promoting bone formation.","line":12},{"title":"@Wildemann_2021_202406171535","target":"@Wildemann_2021_202406171535","line":21},{"title":"@Claes_1998_202406181044","target":"@Claes_1998_202406181044","line":23},{"title":"@Claes_1999_202406181047","target":"@Claes_1999_202406181047","line":25}],"key":"000 Zettelkasten/Interfragmentary strain, experienced by cells embedded in the matrix, influences cellular proliferation and differentiation during the healing process..md"},
